[src:depth-first-search-algorithm/cycle-graph-theory] In graph theory, a **cycle** in a graph is a non-empty trail in which only the first and last vertices are equal.
[src:depth-first-search-algorithm/cycle-graph-theory] A **directed cycle** in a directed graph is a non-empty directed trail in which only the first and last vertices are equal.
[src:depth-first-search-algorithm/cycle-graph-theory] A graph without cycles is called an *acyclic graph*.
[src:depth-first-search-algorithm/cycle-graph-theory] A directed graph without directed cycles is called a *directed acyclic graph*.
[src:depth-first-search-algorithm/cycle-graph-theory] A connected graph without cycles is called a *tree*.
[src:depth-first-search-algorithm/cycle-graph-theory] A chordless cycle in a graph, also called a hole or an induced cycle, is a cycle such that no two vertices of the cycle are connected by an edge that does not itself belong to the cycle.
[src:depth-first-search-algorithm/cycle-graph-theory] An antihole is the complement of a graph hole.
[src:depth-first-search-algorithm/cycle-graph-theory] Chordless cycles may be used to characterize perfect graphs: by the strong perfect graph theorem, a graph is perfect if and only if none of its holes or antiholes have an odd number of vertices that is greater than three.
[src:depth-first-search-algorithm/cycle-graph-theory] A chordal graph, a special type of perfect graph, has no holes of any size greater than three.
[src:depth-first-search-algorithm/cycle-graph-theory] The girth of a graph is the length of its shortest cycle; this cycle is necessarily chordless.
[src:depth-first-search-algorithm/cycle-graph-theory] Cages are defined as the smallest regular graphs with given combinations of degree and girth.
[src:depth-first-search-algorithm/cycle-graph-theory] A peripheral cycle is a cycle in a graph with the property that every two edges not on the cycle can be connected by a path whose interior vertices avoid the cycle.
[src:depth-first-search-algorithm/cycle-graph-theory] In a graph that is not formed by adding one edge to a cycle, a peripheral cycle must be an induced cycle.
[src:depth-first-search-algorithm/cycle-graph-theory] The term *cycle* may also refer to an element of the cycle space of a graph.
[src:depth-first-search-algorithm/cycle-graph-theory] There are many cycle spaces, one for each coefficient field or ring.
[src:depth-first-search-algorithm/cycle-graph-theory] The most common is the *binary cycle space* (usually called simply the *cycle space*), which consists of the edge sets that have even degree at every vertex; it forms a vector space over the two-element field.
[src:depth-first-search-algorithm/cycle-graph-theory] By Veblen's theorem, every element of the cycle space may be formed as an edge-disjoint union of simple cycles.
[src:depth-first-search-algorithm/cycle-graph-theory] A cycle basis of the graph is a set of simple cycles that forms a basis of the cycle space.
[src:depth-first-search-algorithm/cycle-graph-theory] Using ideas from algebraic topology, the binary cycle space generalizes to vector spaces or modules over other rings such as the integers, rational or real numbers, etc.
[src:depth-first-search-algorithm/cycle-graph-theory] The existence of a cycle in directed and undirected graphs can be determined by whether a depth-first search (DFS) finds an edge that points to an ancestor of the current vertex (i.e., it contains a back edge).
[src:depth-first-search-algorithm/cycle-graph-theory] All the back edges which DFS skips over are part of cycles.
[src:depth-first-search-algorithm/cycle-graph-theory] In an undirected graph, the edge to the parent of a node should not be counted as a back edge, but finding any other already visited vertex will indicate a back edge.
[src:depth-first-search-algorithm/cycle-graph-theory] In the case of undirected graphs, only *O*(*n*) time is required to find a cycle in an *n*-vertex graph, since at most *n* − 1 edges can be tree edges.
[src:depth-first-search-algorithm/cycle-graph-theory] Many topological sorting algorithms will detect cycles too, since those are obstacles for topological order to exist.
[src:depth-first-search-algorithm/cycle-graph-theory] Also, if a directed graph has been divided into strongly connected components, cycles only exist within the components and not between them, since cycles are strongly connected.
[src:depth-first-search-algorithm/cycle-graph-theory] For directed graphs, distributed message-based algorithms can be used.
[src:depth-first-search-algorithm/cycle-graph-theory] These algorithms rely on the idea that a message sent by a vertex in a cycle will come back to itself.
[src:depth-first-search-algorithm/cycle-graph-theory] Distributed cycle detection algorithms are useful for processing large-scale graphs using a distributed graph processing system on a computer cluster (or supercomputer).
[src:depth-first-search-algorithm/cycle-graph-theory] Applications of cycle detection include the use of wait-for graphs to detect deadlocks in concurrent systems.
[src:depth-first-search-algorithm/cycle-graph-theory] For undirected graphs, "neighbour" means all vertices connected to *v*, except for the one that recursively called *DFS(v)*.
[src:depth-first-search-algorithm/cycle-graph-theory] This omission prevents the algorithm from finding a trivial cycle of the form *v*→*w*→*v*; these exist in every undirected graph with at least one edge.
[src:depth-first-search-algorithm/cycle-graph-theory] A variant using breadth-first search instead will find a cycle of the smallest possible length.
[src:depth-first-search-algorithm/cycle-graph-theory] The corresponding characterization for the existence of a closed walk visiting each edge exactly once in a directed graph is that the graph be strongly connected and have equal numbers of incoming and outgoing edges at each vertex.
[src:depth-first-search-algorithm/cycle-graph-theory] In either case, the resulting closed trail is known as an Eulerian trail.
[src:depth-first-search-algorithm/cycle-graph-theory] If a finite undirected graph has even degree at each of its vertices, regardless of whether it is connected, then it is possible to find a set of simple cycles that together cover each edge exactly once: this is Veblen's theorem.
[src:depth-first-search-algorithm/cycle-graph-theory] When a connected graph does not meet the conditions of Euler's theorem, a closed walk of minimum length covering each edge at least once can nevertheless be found in polynomial time by solving the route inspection problem.
[src:depth-first-search-algorithm/cycle-graph-theory] The problem of finding a single simple cycle that covers each vertex exactly once, rather than covering the edges, is much harder.
[src:depth-first-search-algorithm/cycle-graph-theory] Such a cycle is known as a Hamiltonian cycle, and determining whether it exists is NP-complete.
[src:depth-first-search-algorithm/cycle-graph-theory] The cycle double cover conjecture states that, for every bridgeless graph, there exists a multiset of simple cycles that covers each edge of the graph exactly twice.
[src:depth-first-search-algorithm/cycle-graph-theory] Proving that this is true (or finding a counterexample) remains an open problem.
[src:depth-first-search-algorithm/cycle-graph-theory] Several important classes of graphs can be defined by or characterized by their cycles.
[src:depth-first-search-algorithm/depth-first-search] A version of depth-first search was investigated in the 19th century by French mathematician Charles Pierre Trémaux as a strategy for solving mazes.
[src:depth-first-search-algorithm/depth-first-search] The time and space analysis of DFS differs according to its application area.
[src:depth-first-search-algorithm/depth-first-search] In theoretical computer science, DFS is typically used to traverse an entire graph, and takes time $O(|V|+|E|)$ , where $|V|$ is the number of vertices and $|E|$ the number of edges.
[src:depth-first-search-algorithm/depth-first-search] This is linear in the size of the graph.
[src:depth-first-search-algorithm/depth-first-search] In these applications it also uses space $O(|V|)$ in the worst case to store the stack of vertices on the current search path as well as the set of already-visited vertices.
[src:depth-first-search-algorithm/depth-first-search] Thus, in this setting, the time and space bounds are the same as for breadth-first search and the choice of which of these two algorithms to use depends less on their complexity and more on the different properties of the vertex orderings the two algorithms produce.
[src:depth-first-search-algorithm/depth-first-search] For applications of DFS in relation to specific domains, such as searching for solutions in artificial intelligence or web-crawling, the graph to be traversed is often either too large to visit in its entirety or infinite (DFS may suffer from non-termination).
[src:depth-first-search-algorithm/depth-first-search] In such cases, search is only performed to a limited depth; due to limited resources, such as memory or disk space, one typically does not use data structures to keep track of the set of all previously visited vertices.
[src:depth-first-search-algorithm/depth-first-search] For such applications, DFS also lends itself much better to heuristic methods for choosing a likely-looking branch.
[src:depth-first-search-algorithm/depth-first-search] When an appropriate depth limit is not known a priori, iterative deepening depth-first search applies DFS repeatedly with a sequence of increasing limits.
[src:depth-first-search-algorithm/depth-first-search] In the artificial intelligence mode of analysis, with a branching factor greater than one, iterative deepening increases the running time by only a constant factor over the case in which the correct depth limit is known due to the geometric growth of the number of nodes per level.
[src:depth-first-search-algorithm/depth-first-search] DFS may also be used to collect a sample of graph nodes.
[src:depth-first-search-algorithm/depth-first-search] However, incomplete DFS, similarly to incomplete BFS, is biased towards nodes of high degree.
[src:depth-first-search-algorithm/depth-first-search] The edges traversed in this search form a Trémaux tree, a structure with important applications in graph theory.
[src:depth-first-search-algorithm/depth-first-search] Performing the same search without remembering previously visited nodes results in visiting the nodes in the order A, B, D, F, E, A, B, D, F, E, etc. forever, caught in the A, B, D, F, E cycle and never reaching C or G.
[src:depth-first-search-algorithm/depth-first-search] Iterative deepening is one technique to avoid this infinite loop and would reach all nodes.
[src:depth-first-search-algorithm/depth-first-search] The result of a depth-first search of a graph can be conveniently described in terms of a spanning tree of the vertices reached during the search.
[src:depth-first-search-algorithm/depth-first-search] Based on this spanning tree, the edges of the original graph can be divided into three classes: **forward edges**, which point from a node of the tree to one of its descendants, **back edges**, which point from a node to one of its ancestors, and **cross edges**, which do neither.
[src:depth-first-search-algorithm/depth-first-search] Sometimes **tree edges**, edges which belong to the spanning tree itself, are classified separately from forward edges.
[src:depth-first-search-algorithm/depth-first-search] If the original graph is undirected then all of its edges are tree edges or back edges.
[src:depth-first-search-algorithm/depth-first-search] It is also possible to use depth-first search to linearly order the vertices of a graph or tree.
[src:depth-first-search-algorithm/depth-first-search] For binary trees there is additionally **in-ordering** and **reverse in-ordering**.
[src:depth-first-search-algorithm/depth-first-search] For example, when searching the directed graph below beginning at node A, the sequence of traversals is either A B D B A C A or A C D C A B A (choosing to first visit B or C from A is up to the algorithm).
[src:depth-first-search-algorithm/depth-first-search] Note that repeat visits in the form of backtracking to a node, to check if it has still unvisited neighbors, are included here (even if it is found to have none).
[src:depth-first-search-algorithm/depth-first-search] Thus the possible preorderings are A B D C and A C D B, while the possible postorderings are D B C A and D C B A, and the possible reverse postorderings are A C B D and A B C D.
[src:depth-first-search-algorithm/depth-first-search] Reverse postordering produces a topological sorting of any directed acyclic graph.
[src:depth-first-search-algorithm/depth-first-search] This ordering is also useful in control-flow analysis as it often represents a natural linearization of the control flows.
[src:depth-first-search-algorithm/depth-first-search] The graph above might represent the flow of control in the code fragment below, and it is natural to consider this code in the order A B C D or A C B D but not natural to use the order A B D C or A C D B.
[src:depth-first-search-algorithm/depth-first-search] The recursive implementation will visit the nodes from the example graph in the following order: A, B, D, F, E, C, G.
[src:depth-first-search-algorithm/depth-first-search] The non-recursive implementation will visit the nodes as: A, E, F, B, D, C, G.
[src:depth-first-search-algorithm/depth-first-search] 2. it delays checking whether a vertex has been discovered until the vertex is popped from the stack rather than making this check before adding the vertex.
[src:depth-first-search-algorithm/depth-first-search] If G is a tree, replacing the queue of the breadth-first search algorithm with a stack will yield a depth-first search algorithm.
[src:depth-first-search-algorithm/depth-first-search] For general graphs, replacing the stack of the iterative depth-first search implementation with a queue would also produce a breadth-first search algorithm, although a somewhat nonstandard one.
[src:depth-first-search-algorithm/depth-first-search] Another possible implementation of iterative depth-first search uses a stack of iterators of the list of neighbors of a node, instead of a stack of nodes.
[src:depth-first-search-algorithm/depth-first-search] This yields the same traversal as recursive DFS.
[src:depth-first-search-algorithm/depth-first-search] The computational complexity of DFS was investigated by John Reif.
[src:depth-first-search-algorithm/depth-first-search] More precisely, given a graph G , let $O=(v_{1},\dots ,v_{n})$ be the ordering computed by the standard recursive DFS algorithm.
[src:depth-first-search-algorithm/depth-first-search] This ordering is called the lexicographic depth-first search ordering.
[src:depth-first-search-algorithm/depth-first-search] John Reif considered the complexity of computing the lexicographic depth-first search ordering, given a graph and a source.
[src:depth-first-search-algorithm/depth-first-search] A decision version of the problem (testing whether some vertex u occurs before some vertex v in this order) is **P**-complete, meaning that it is "a nightmare for parallel processing".
[src:depth-first-search-algorithm/depth-first-search] A depth-first search ordering (not necessarily the lexicographic one), can be computed by a randomized parallel algorithm in the complexity class RNC.
[src:depth-first-search-algorithm/depth-first-search] As of 1997, it remained unknown whether a depth-first traversal could be constructed by a deterministic parallel algorithm, in the complexity class NC.
[src:depth-first-search-algorithm/graph-traversal] In computer science, **graph traversal** (also known as **graph search**) refers to the process of visiting (checking and/or updating) each vertex in a graph.
[src:depth-first-search-algorithm/graph-traversal] Such traversals are classified by the order in which the vertices are visited.
[src:depth-first-search-algorithm/graph-traversal] Tree traversal is a special case of graph traversal.
[src:depth-first-search-algorithm/graph-traversal] Unlike tree traversal, graph traversal may require that some vertices be visited more than once, since it is not necessarily known before transitioning to a vertex that it has already been explored.
[src:depth-first-search-algorithm/graph-traversal] As graphs become more dense, this redundancy becomes more prevalent, causing computation time to increase; as graphs become more sparse, the opposite holds true.
[src:depth-first-search-algorithm/graph-traversal] Thus, it is usually necessary to remember which vertices have already been explored by the algorithm, so that vertices are revisited as infrequently as possible (or in the worst case, to prevent the traversal from continuing indefinitely).
[src:depth-first-search-algorithm/graph-traversal] This may be accomplished by associating each vertex of the graph with a "color" or "visitation" state during the traversal, which is then checked and updated as the algorithm visits each vertex.
[src:depth-first-search-algorithm/graph-traversal] If the vertex has already been visited, it is ignored and the path is pursued no further; otherwise, the algorithm checks/updates the vertex and continues down its current path.
[src:depth-first-search-algorithm/graph-traversal] Several special cases of graphs imply the visitation of other vertices in their structure, and thus do not require that visitation be explicitly recorded during the traversal.
[src:depth-first-search-algorithm/graph-traversal] An important example of this is a tree: during a traversal it may be assumed that all "ancestor" vertices of the current vertex (and others depending on the algorithm) have already been visited.
[src:depth-first-search-algorithm/graph-traversal] Both the depth-first and breadth-first graph searches are adaptations of tree-based algorithms, distinguished primarily by the lack of a structurally determined "root" vertex and the addition of a data structure to record the traversal's visitation state.
[src:depth-first-search-algorithm/graph-traversal] Note. — If each vertex in a graph is to be traversed by a tree-based algorithm (such as DFS or BFS), then the algorithm must be called at least once for each connected component of the graph.
[src:depth-first-search-algorithm/graph-traversal] This is easily accomplished by iterating through all the vertices of the graph, performing the algorithm on each vertex that is still unvisited when examined.
[src:depth-first-search-algorithm/graph-traversal] A depth-first search (DFS) is an algorithm for traversing a finite graph.
[src:depth-first-search-algorithm/graph-traversal] DFS visits the child vertices before visiting the sibling vertices; that is, it traverses the depth of any particular path before exploring its breadth.
[src:depth-first-search-algorithm/graph-traversal] A stack (often the program's call stack via recursion) is generally used when implementing the algorithm.
[src:depth-first-search-algorithm/graph-traversal] The algorithm begins with a chosen "root" vertex; it then iteratively transitions from the current vertex to an adjacent, unvisited vertex, until it can no longer find an unexplored vertex to transition to from its current location.
[src:depth-first-search-algorithm/graph-traversal] The algorithm then backtracks along previously visited vertices, until it finds a vertex connected to yet more uncharted territory.
[src:depth-first-search-algorithm/graph-traversal] It will then proceed down the new path as it had before, backtracking as it encounters dead-ends, and ending only when the algorithm has backtracked past the original "root" vertex from the very first step.
[src:depth-first-search-algorithm/graph-traversal] DFS is the basis for many graph-related algorithms, including topological sorts and planarity testing.
[src:depth-first-search-algorithm/graph-traversal] A breadth-first search (BFS) is another technique for traversing a finite graph.
[src:depth-first-search-algorithm/graph-traversal] BFS visits the sibling vertices before visiting the child vertices, and a queue is used in the search process.
[src:depth-first-search-algorithm/graph-traversal] This algorithm is often used to find the shortest path from one vertex to another.
[src:depth-first-search-algorithm/graph-traversal] The problem of graph exploration can be seen as a variant of graph traversal.
[src:depth-first-search-algorithm/graph-traversal] It is an online problem, meaning that the information about the graph is only revealed during the runtime of the algorithm.
[src:depth-first-search-algorithm/graph-traversal] A common model is as follows: given a connected graph *G* = (*V*, *E*) with non-negative edge weights.
[src:depth-first-search-algorithm/graph-traversal] The algorithm starts at some vertex, and knows all incident outgoing edges and the vertices at the end of these edges—but not more.
[src:depth-first-search-algorithm/graph-traversal] When a new vertex is visited, then again all incident outgoing edges and the vertices at the end are known.
[src:depth-first-search-algorithm/graph-traversal] The goal is to visit all *n* vertices and return to the starting vertex, but the sum of the weights of the tour should be as small as possible.
[src:depth-first-search-algorithm/graph-traversal] The problem can also be understood as a specific version of the travelling salesman problem, where the salesman has to discover the graph on the go.
[src:depth-first-search-algorithm/graph-traversal] A *universal traversal sequence* is a sequence of instructions comprising a graph traversal for any regular graph with a set number of vertices and for any starting vertex.
[src:depth-first-search-algorithm/graph-traversal] A probabilistic proof was used by Aleliunas et al. to show that there exists a universal traversal sequence with number of instructions proportional to *O*(*n*5) for any regular graph with *n* vertices.
[src:depth-first-search-algorithm/graph-traversal] The steps specified in the sequence are relative to the current node, not absolute.
[src:depth-first-search-algorithm/graph-traversal] For example, if the current node is *v**j*, and *v**j* has *d* neighbors, then the traversal sequence will specify the next node to visit, *v**j*+1, as the *i*th neighbor of *v**j*, where 1 ≤ *i* ≤ *d*.
[src:depth-first-search-algorithm/iterative-deepening-depth-first-search] In computer science, **iterative deepening search** or more specifically **iterative deepening depth-first search** (IDS or IDDFS) is a state space/graph search strategy in which a depth-limited version of depth-first search is run repeatedly with increasing depth limits until the goal is found.
[src:depth-first-search-algorithm/iterative-deepening-depth-first-search] IDDFS is optimal, meaning that it finds the shallowest goal.
[src:depth-first-search-algorithm/iterative-deepening-depth-first-search] Since it visits all the nodes in the search tree down to depth d before visiting any nodes at depth $d+1$ , the cumulative order in which nodes are first visited is effectively the same as in breadth-first search.
[src:depth-first-search-algorithm/iterative-deepening-depth-first-search] The following pseudocode shows IDDFS implemented in terms of a recursive depth-limited DFS (called DLS) for directed graphs.
[src:depth-first-search-algorithm/iterative-deepening-depth-first-search] This implementation of IDDFS does not account for already-visited nodes.
[src:depth-first-search-algorithm/iterative-deepening-depth-first-search] If the goal node is found by DLS, IDDFS will return it without looking deeper.
[src:depth-first-search-algorithm/iterative-deepening-depth-first-search] Otherwise, if at least one node exists at that level of depth, the *remaining* flag will let IDDFS continue.
[src:depth-first-search-algorithm/iterative-deepening-depth-first-search] 2-tuples are useful as return value to signal IDDFS to continue deepening or stop, in case tree depth and goal membership are unknown *a priori*.
[src:depth-first-search-algorithm/iterative-deepening-depth-first-search] Another solution could use sentinel values instead to represent *not found* or *remaining level* results.
[src:depth-first-search-algorithm/iterative-deepening-depth-first-search] IDDFS achieves breadth-first search's completeness (when the branching factor is finite) using depth-first search's space-efficiency.
[src:depth-first-search-algorithm/iterative-deepening-depth-first-search] If a solution exists, it will find a solution path with the fewest arcs.
[src:depth-first-search-algorithm/iterative-deepening-depth-first-search] Iterative deepening visits states multiple times, and it may seem wasteful.
[src:depth-first-search-algorithm/iterative-deepening-depth-first-search] However, if IDDFS explores a search tree to depth d , most of the total effort is in exploring the states at depth d .
[src:depth-first-search-algorithm/iterative-deepening-depth-first-search] Relative to the number of states at depth d , the cost of repeatedly visiting the states above this depth is always small.
[src:depth-first-search-algorithm/iterative-deepening-depth-first-search] For example, alpha–beta pruning is most efficient if it searches the best moves first.
[src:depth-first-search-algorithm/iterative-deepening-depth-first-search] A second advantage is the responsiveness of the algorithm.
[src:depth-first-search-algorithm/iterative-deepening-depth-first-search] Because early iterations use small values for d , they execute extremely quickly.
[src:depth-first-search-algorithm/iterative-deepening-depth-first-search] This allows the algorithm to supply early indications of the result almost immediately, followed by refinements as d increases.
[src:depth-first-search-algorithm/iterative-deepening-depth-first-search] When used in an interactive setting, such as in a chess-playing program, this facility allows the program to play at any time with the current best move found in the search it has completed so far.
[src:depth-first-search-algorithm/iterative-deepening-depth-first-search] This can be phrased as each depth of the search *co*recursively producing a better approximation of the solution, though the work done at each step is recursive.
[src:depth-first-search-algorithm/iterative-deepening-depth-first-search] This is not possible with a traditional depth-first search, which does not produce intermediate results.
[src:depth-first-search-algorithm/iterative-deepening-depth-first-search] The time complexity of IDDFS in a (well-balanced) tree works out to be the same as breadth-first search, i.e. $O(b^{d})$ , where b is the branching factor and d is the depth of the goal.
[src:depth-first-search-algorithm/iterative-deepening-depth-first-search] In an iterative deepening search, the nodes at depth d are expanded once, those at depth $d-1$ are expanded twice, and so on up to the root of the search tree, which is expanded $d+1$ times.
[src:depth-first-search-algorithm/iterative-deepening-depth-first-search] where $b^{d}$ is the number of expansions at depth d , $2b^{d-1}$ is the number of expansions at depth $d-1$ , and so on.
[src:depth-first-search-algorithm/iterative-deepening-depth-first-search] Since $(1-x)^{-2}$ or $\left(1-{\frac {1}{b}}\right)^{-2}$ is a constant independent of d (the depth), if $b>1$ (i.e., if the branching factor is greater than 1), the running time of the depth-first iterative deepening search is $O(b^{d})$ .
[src:depth-first-search-algorithm/iterative-deepening-depth-first-search] All together, an iterative deepening search from depth 1 all the way down to depth d expands only about $11\%$ more nodes than a single breadth-first or depth-limited search to depth d , when $b=10$ .
[src:depth-first-search-algorithm/iterative-deepening-depth-first-search] The higher the branching factor, the lower the overhead of repeatedly expanded states, but even when the branching factor is 2, iterative deepening search only takes about twice as long as a complete breadth-first search.
[src:depth-first-search-algorithm/iterative-deepening-depth-first-search] This means that the time complexity of iterative deepening is still $O(b^{d})$ .
[src:depth-first-search-algorithm/iterative-deepening-depth-first-search] The space complexity of IDDFS is $O(d)$ , where d is the depth of the goal.
[src:depth-first-search-algorithm/iterative-deepening-depth-first-search] Since IDDFS, at any point, is engaged in a depth-first search, it need only store a stack of nodes which represents the branch of the tree it is expanding.
[src:depth-first-search-algorithm/iterative-deepening-depth-first-search] Since it finds a solution of optimal length, the maximum depth of this stack is d , and hence the maximum amount of space is $O(d)$ .
[src:depth-first-search-algorithm/iterative-deepening-depth-first-search] In general, iterative deepening is the preferred search method when there is a large search space and the depth of the solution is not known.
[src:depth-first-search-algorithm/iterative-deepening-depth-first-search] a depth-first search starting at A, assuming that the left edges in the shown graph are chosen before right edges, and assuming the search remembers previously-visited nodes and will not repeat them (since this is a small graph), will visit the nodes in the following order: A, B, D, F, E, C, G.
[src:depth-first-search-algorithm/iterative-deepening-depth-first-search] Performing the same search without remembering previously visited nodes results in visiting nodes in the order A, B, D, F, E, A, B, D, F, E, etc. forever, caught in the A, B, D, F, E cycle and never reaching C or G.
[src:depth-first-search-algorithm/iterative-deepening-depth-first-search] (It still sees C, but that it came later.
[src:depth-first-search-algorithm/iterative-deepening-depth-first-search] For this graph, as more depth is added, the two cycles "ABFE" and "AEFB" will simply get longer before the algorithm gives up and tries another branch.
[src:depth-first-search-algorithm/iterative-deepening-depth-first-search] Similar to iterative deepening is a search strategy called iterative lengthening search that works with increasing path-cost limits instead of depth-limits.
[src:depth-first-search-algorithm/iterative-deepening-depth-first-search] It expands nodes in the order of increasing path cost; therefore the first goal it encounters is the one with the cheapest path cost.
[src:depth-first-search-algorithm/iterative-deepening-depth-first-search] But iterative lengthening incurs substantial overhead that makes it less useful than iterative deepening.
[src:depth-first-search-algorithm/iterative-deepening-depth-first-search] Iterative deepening A* is a best-first search that performs iterative deepening based on "f"-values similar to the ones computed in the A* algorithm.
[src:depth-first-search-algorithm/iterative-deepening-depth-first-search] IDDFS has a bidirectional counterpart, which alternates two searches: one starting from the source node and moving along the directed arcs, and another one starting from the target node and proceeding along the directed arcs in opposite direction (from the arc's head node to the arc's tail node).
[src:depth-first-search-algorithm/iterative-deepening-depth-first-search] The search process first checks that the source node and the target node are same, and if so, returns the trivial path consisting of a single source/target node.
[src:depth-first-search-algorithm/iterative-deepening-depth-first-search] Otherwise, the forward search process expands the child nodes of the source node (set A ), the backward search process expands the parent nodes of the target node (set B ), and it is checked whether A and B intersect.
[src:depth-first-search-algorithm/iterative-deepening-depth-first-search] Otherwise, the search depth is incremented and the same computation takes place.
[src:depth-first-search-algorithm/iterative-deepening-depth-first-search] One limitation of the algorithm is that the shortest path consisting of an odd number of arcs will not be detected.
[src:depth-first-search-algorithm/iterative-deepening-depth-first-search] Suppose we have a shortest path $\langle s,u,v,t\rangle .$ When the depth will reach two hops along the arcs, the forward search will proceed from u to v , and the backward search will proceed from v to u .
[src:depth-first-search-algorithm/iterative-deepening-depth-first-search] Pictorially, the search frontiers will go through each other, and instead a suboptimal path consisting of an even number of arcs will be returned.
[src:depth-first-search-algorithm/iterative-deepening-depth-first-search] What comes to space complexity, the algorithm colors the deepest nodes in the forward search process in order to detect existence of the middle node where the two search processes meet.
[src:depth-first-search-algorithm/iterative-deepening-depth-first-search] Additional difficulty of applying bidirectional IDDFS is that if the source and the target nodes are in different strongly connected components, say, $s\in S,t\in T$ , if there is no arc leaving S and entering T , the search will never terminate.
[src:depth-first-search-algorithm/iterative-deepening-depth-first-search] where n is the number of nodes in the shortest $s,t$ -path.
[src:depth-first-search-algorithm/stack-abstract-data-type] Additionally, a peek operation can, without modifying the stack, return the value of the last element added (the item at the top of the stack).
[src:depth-first-search-algorithm/stack-abstract-data-type] The name *stack* is an analogy to a set of physical items stacked one atop another, such as a stack of plates.
[src:depth-first-search-algorithm/stack-abstract-data-type] The order in which elements are added to or removed from a stack is described as **last in, first out**, referred to by the acronym **LIFO**.
[src:depth-first-search-algorithm/stack-abstract-data-type] As with a stack of physical objects, this structure makes it easy to take an item off the top of the stack, but accessing a datum deeper in the stack may require removing multiple other items first.
[src:depth-first-search-algorithm/stack-abstract-data-type] Considered a sequential collection, a stack has one end which is the only position at which the push and pop operations may occur, the *top* of the stack, and is fixed at the other end, the *bottom*.
[src:depth-first-search-algorithm/stack-abstract-data-type] A stack may be implemented as, for example, a singly linked list with a pointer to the top element.
[src:depth-first-search-algorithm/stack-abstract-data-type] A stack may be implemented to have a bounded capacity.
[src:depth-first-search-algorithm/stack-abstract-data-type] If the stack is full and does not contain enough space to accept another element, the stack is in a state of stack overflow.
[src:depth-first-search-algorithm/stack-abstract-data-type] Stacks entered the computer science literature in 1946, when Alan Turing used the terms "bury" and "unbury" as a means of calling and returning from subroutines.
[src:depth-first-search-algorithm/stack-abstract-data-type] Subroutines and a two-level stack had already been implemented in Konrad Zuse's Z4 in 1945.
[src:depth-first-search-algorithm/stack-abstract-data-type] Bauer of the Technical University of Munich proposed the idea of a stack called *Operationskeller* ("operational cellar") in 1955 and filed a patent in 1957.
[src:depth-first-search-algorithm/stack-abstract-data-type] In March 1988, by which time Samelson was deceased, Bauer received the IEEE Computer Pioneer Award for the invention of the stack principle.
[src:depth-first-search-algorithm/stack-abstract-data-type] Similar concepts were independently developed by Charles Leonard Hamblin in the first half of 1954 and by Wilhelm Kämmerer with his *automatisches Gedächtnis* ("automatic memory") in 1958.
[src:depth-first-search-algorithm/stack-abstract-data-type] Stacks are often described using the analogy of a spring-loaded stack of plates in a cafeteria.
[src:depth-first-search-algorithm/stack-abstract-data-type] Clean plates are placed on top of the stack, pushing down any plates already there.
[src:depth-first-search-algorithm/stack-abstract-data-type] When the top plate is removed from the stack, the one below it is elevated to become the new top plate.
[src:depth-first-search-algorithm/stack-abstract-data-type] In many implementations, a stack has more operations than the essential "push" and "pop" operations.
[src:depth-first-search-algorithm/stack-abstract-data-type] An example of a non-essential operation is "top of stack", or "peek", which observes the top element without removing it from the stack.
[src:depth-first-search-algorithm/stack-abstract-data-type] Since this can be broken down into a "pop" followed by a "push" to return the same data to the stack, it is not considered an essential operation.
[src:depth-first-search-algorithm/stack-abstract-data-type] If the stack is empty, an underflow condition will occur upon execution of either the "peek" or "pop" operation.
[src:depth-first-search-algorithm/stack-abstract-data-type] Additionally, many implementations include convenience operations that handle common tasks, such as checking if the stack is empty or returning its size.
[src:depth-first-search-algorithm/stack-abstract-data-type] A stack can be easily implemented either through an array or a linked list, as it is merely a special case of a list.
[src:depth-first-search-algorithm/stack-abstract-data-type] In either case, what identifies the data structure as a stack is not the implementation but the interface: the user is only allowed to pop or push items onto the array or linked list, with few other helper operations.
[src:depth-first-search-algorithm/stack-abstract-data-type] The following will demonstrate both implementations using pseudocode.
[src:depth-first-search-algorithm/stack-abstract-data-type] An array can be used to implement a (bounded) stack, as follows.
[src:depth-first-search-algorithm/stack-abstract-data-type] The first element, usually at the zero offset, is the bottom, resulting in `array[0]` being the first element pushed onto the stack and the last element popped off.
[src:depth-first-search-algorithm/stack-abstract-data-type] The program must keep track of the size (length) of the stack, using a variable *top* that records the number of items pushed so far, therefore pointing to the place in the array where the next element is to be inserted (assuming a zero-based index convention).
[src:depth-first-search-algorithm/stack-abstract-data-type] Using a dynamic array, it is possible to implement a stack that can grow or shrink as much as needed.
[src:depth-first-search-algorithm/stack-abstract-data-type] The size of the stack is simply the size of the dynamic array, which is a very efficient implementation of a stack since adding items to or removing items from the end of a dynamic array requires amortized O(1) time.
[src:depth-first-search-algorithm/stack-abstract-data-type] Another option for implementing stacks is to use a singly linked list.
[src:depth-first-search-algorithm/stack-abstract-data-type] Some languages, such as Perl, LISP, JavaScript and Python, make the stack operations push and pop available on their standard list/array types.
[src:depth-first-search-algorithm/stack-abstract-data-type] Some languages, notably those in the Forth family (including PostScript), are designed around language-defined stacks that are directly visible to and manipulated by the programmer.
[src:depth-first-search-algorithm/stack-abstract-data-type] Several of the C++ Standard Library container types have `push_back()` and `pop_back()` operations with LIFO semantics; additionally, the `std::stack` template class adapts existing containers to provide a restricted API with only push/pop operations.
[src:depth-first-search-algorithm/stack-abstract-data-type] Java's library contains a `Stack` class that is a specialization of `Vector`.
[src:depth-first-search-algorithm/stack-abstract-data-type] Following is an example program in Java language, using that class.
[src:depth-first-search-algorithm/stack-abstract-data-type] Some processors, such as the PDP-11, VAX, and Motorola 68000 series have addressing modes useful for stack manipulation.
[src:depth-first-search-algorithm/stack-abstract-data-type] The following trivial PDP-11 assembly source code pushes two numbers on a stack and adds them, leaving the result on the stack.
[src:depth-first-search-algorithm/stack-abstract-data-type] A common use of stacks at the architecture level is as a means of allocating and accessing memory.
[src:depth-first-search-algorithm/stack-abstract-data-type] A typical stack is an area of computer memory with a fixed origin and a variable size.
[src:depth-first-search-algorithm/stack-abstract-data-type] Initially the size of the stack is zero.
[src:depth-first-search-algorithm/stack-abstract-data-type] A stack pointer (usually in the form of a processor register) points to the most recently referenced location on the stack; when the stack has a size of zero, the stack pointer points to the origin of the stack.
[src:depth-first-search-algorithm/stack-abstract-data-type] There are many variations on the basic principle of stack operations.
[src:depth-first-search-algorithm/stack-abstract-data-type] Every stack has a fixed location in memory at which it begins.
[src:depth-first-search-algorithm/stack-abstract-data-type] As data items are added to the stack, the stack pointer is displaced to indicate the current extent of the stack, which expands away from the origin.
[src:depth-first-search-algorithm/stack-abstract-data-type] Stack pointers may point to the origin of a stack or to a limited range of addresses above or below the origin (depending on the direction in which the stack grows); however, the stack pointer cannot cross the origin of the stack.
[src:depth-first-search-algorithm/stack-abstract-data-type] In other words, if the origin of the stack is at address 1000 and the stack grows downwards (towards addresses 999, 998, and so on), the stack pointer must never be incremented beyond 1000 (to 1001 or beyond).
[src:depth-first-search-algorithm/stack-abstract-data-type] If a pop operation on the stack causes the stack pointer to move past the origin of the stack, a *stack underflow* occurs.
[src:depth-first-search-algorithm/stack-abstract-data-type] If a push operation causes the stack pointer to increment or decrement beyond the maximum extent of the stack, a *stack overflow* occurs.
[src:depth-first-search-algorithm/stack-abstract-data-type] Stacks are often visualized growing from the bottom up (like real-world stacks).
[src:depth-first-search-algorithm/stack-abstract-data-type] They may also be visualized growing from left to right, where the top is on the far right, or even growing from top to bottom.
[src:depth-first-search-algorithm/stack-abstract-data-type] The important feature is for the bottom of the stack to be in a fixed position.
[src:depth-first-search-algorithm/stack-abstract-data-type] The illustration in this section is an example of a top-to-bottom growth visualization: the top (28) is the stack "bottom", since the stack "top" (9) is where items are pushed or popped from.
[src:depth-first-search-algorithm/stack-abstract-data-type] A *right rotate* will move the first element to the third position, the second to the first and the third to the second.
[src:depth-first-search-algorithm/stack-abstract-data-type] A stack is usually represented in computers by a block of memory cells, with the "bottom" at a fixed location, and the stack pointer holding the address of the current "top" cell in the stack.
[src:depth-first-search-algorithm/stack-abstract-data-type] The "top" and "bottom" nomenclature is used irrespective of whether the stack actually grows towards higher memory addresses.
[src:depth-first-search-algorithm/stack-abstract-data-type] Pushing an item on to the stack adjusts the stack pointer by the size of the item (either decrementing or incrementing, depending on the direction in which the stack grows in memory), pointing it to the next cell, and copies the new top item to the stack area.
[src:depth-first-search-algorithm/stack-abstract-data-type] Depending again on the exact implementation, at the end of a push operation, the stack pointer may point to the next unused location in the stack, or it may point to the topmost item in the stack.
[src:depth-first-search-algorithm/stack-abstract-data-type] If the stack points to the current topmost item, the stack pointer will be updated before a new item is pushed onto the stack; if it points to the next available location in the stack, it will be updated *after* the new item is pushed onto the stack.
[src:depth-first-search-algorithm/stack-abstract-data-type] Popping the stack is simply the inverse of pushing.
[src:depth-first-search-algorithm/stack-abstract-data-type] The topmost item in the stack is removed and the stack pointer is updated, in the opposite order of that used in the push operation.
[src:depth-first-search-algorithm/stack-abstract-data-type] Many CISC-type CPU designs, including the x86, Z80 and 6502, have a dedicated register for use as the call stack stack pointer with dedicated call, return, push, and pop instructions that implicitly update the dedicated register, thus increasing code density.
[src:depth-first-search-algorithm/stack-abstract-data-type] Some CISC processors, like the PDP-11 and the 68000, also have special addressing modes for implementation of stacks, typically with a semi-dedicated stack pointer as well (such as A7 in the 68000).
[src:depth-first-search-algorithm/stack-abstract-data-type] In contrast, most RISC CPU designs do not have dedicated stack instructions and therefore most, if not all, registers may be used as stack pointers as needed.
[src:depth-first-search-algorithm/stack-abstract-data-type] Some machines use a stack for arithmetic and logical operations; operands are pushed onto the stack, and arithmetic and logical operations act on the top one or more items on the stack, popping them off the stack and pushing the result onto the stack.
[src:depth-first-search-algorithm/stack-abstract-data-type] Machines that function in this fashion are called stack machines.
[src:depth-first-search-algorithm/stack-abstract-data-type] A number of mainframes and minicomputers were stack machines, the most famous being the Burroughs Large Systems.
[src:depth-first-search-algorithm/stack-abstract-data-type] Other examples include the CISC HP 3000 machines and the CISC machines from Tandem Computers.
[src:depth-first-search-algorithm/stack-abstract-data-type] The x87 floating-point architecture is an example of a set of registers organised as a stack where direct access to individual registers (relative to the current top) is also possible.
[src:depth-first-search-algorithm/stack-abstract-data-type] Having the top-of-stack as an implicit argument allows for a small machine code footprint with a good usage of bus bandwidth and code caches, but it also prevents some types of optimizations possible on processors permitting random access to the register file for all (two or three) operands.
[src:depth-first-search-algorithm/stack-abstract-data-type] A stack structure also makes superscalar implementations with register renaming (for speculative execution) somewhat more complex to implement, although it is still feasible, as exemplified by modern x87 implementations.
[src:depth-first-search-algorithm/stack-abstract-data-type] Sun SPARC, AMD Am29000, and Intel i960 are all examples of architectures that use register windows within a register-stack as another strategy to avoid the use of slow main memory for function arguments and return values.
[src:depth-first-search-algorithm/stack-abstract-data-type] There is also a number of small microprocessors that implement a stack directly in hardware, and some microcontrollers have a fixed-depth stack that is not directly accessible.
[src:depth-first-search-algorithm/stack-abstract-data-type] Examples are the PIC microcontrollers, the Computer Cowboys MuP21, the Harris RTX line, and the Novix NC4016.
[src:depth-first-search-algorithm/stack-abstract-data-type] At least one microcontroller family, the COP400, implements a stack either directly in hardware or in RAM via a stack pointer, depending on the device.
[src:depth-first-search-algorithm/stack-abstract-data-type] Many stack-based microprocessors were used to implement the programming language Forth at the microcode level.
[src:depth-first-search-algorithm/stack-abstract-data-type] Calculators that employ reverse Polish notation use a stack structure to hold values.
[src:depth-first-search-algorithm/stack-abstract-data-type] Expressions can be represented in prefix, postfix or infix notations and conversion from one form to another may be accomplished using a stack.
[src:depth-first-search-algorithm/stack-abstract-data-type] Many compilers use a stack to parse syntax before translation into low-level code.
[src:depth-first-search-algorithm/stack-abstract-data-type] Most programming languages are context-free languages, allowing them to be parsed with stack-based machines.
[src:depth-first-search-algorithm/stack-abstract-data-type] Another important application of stacks is backtracking.
[src:depth-first-search-algorithm/stack-abstract-data-type] An illustration of this is the simple example of finding the correct path in a maze that contains a series of points, a starting point, several paths and a destination.
[src:depth-first-search-algorithm/stack-abstract-data-type] If random paths must be chosen, then after following an incorrect path, there must be a method by which to return to the beginning of that path.
[src:depth-first-search-algorithm/stack-abstract-data-type] This can be achieved through the use of stacks, as a last correct point can be pushed onto the stack, and popped from the stack in case of an incorrect path.
[src:depth-first-search-algorithm/stack-abstract-data-type] The prototypical example of a backtracking algorithm is depth-first search, which finds all vertices of a graph that can be reached from a specified starting vertex.
[src:depth-first-search-algorithm/stack-abstract-data-type] Other applications of backtracking involve searching through spaces that represent potential solutions to an optimization problem.
[src:depth-first-search-algorithm/stack-abstract-data-type] Branch and bound is a technique for performing such backtracking searches without exhaustively searching all of the potential solutions in such a space.
[src:depth-first-search-algorithm/stack-abstract-data-type] A number of programming languages are stack-oriented, meaning they define most basic operations (adding two numbers, printing a character) as taking their arguments from the stack, and placing any return values back on the stack.
[src:depth-first-search-algorithm/stack-abstract-data-type] For example, PostScript has a return stack and an operand stack, and also has a graphics state stack and a dictionary stack.
[src:depth-first-search-algorithm/stack-abstract-data-type] Many virtual machines are also stack-oriented, including the p-code machine and the Java Virtual Machine.
[src:depth-first-search-algorithm/stack-abstract-data-type] The functions follow a runtime protocol between caller and callee to save arguments and return value on the stack.
[src:depth-first-search-algorithm/stack-abstract-data-type] Stacks are an important way of supporting nested or recursive function calls.
[src:depth-first-search-algorithm/stack-abstract-data-type] This type of stack is used implicitly by the compiler to support CALL and RETURN statements (or their equivalents) and is not manipulated directly by the programmer.
[src:depth-first-search-algorithm/stack-abstract-data-type] Some programming languages use the stack to store data that is local to a procedure.
[src:depth-first-search-algorithm/stack-abstract-data-type] Space for local data items is allocated from the stack when the procedure is entered, and is deallocated when the procedure exits.
[src:depth-first-search-algorithm/stack-abstract-data-type] The C programming language is typically implemented in this way.
[src:depth-first-search-algorithm/stack-abstract-data-type] Using the same stack for both data and procedure calls has important security implications (see below) of which a programmer must be aware in order to avoid introducing serious security bugs into a program.
[src:depth-first-search-algorithm/stack-abstract-data-type] Several algorithms use a stack (separate from the usual function call stack of most programming languages) as the principal data structure with which they organize their information.
[src:depth-first-search-algorithm/stack-abstract-data-type] Some computing environments use stacks in ways that may make them vulnerable to security breaches and attacks.
[src:depth-first-search-algorithm/stack-abstract-data-type] Programmers working in such environments must take special care to avoid such pitfalls in these implementations.
[src:depth-first-search-algorithm/stack-abstract-data-type] As an example, some programming languages use a common stack to store both data local to a called procedure and the linking information that allows the procedure to return to its caller.
[src:depth-first-search-algorithm/stack-abstract-data-type] This means that the program moves data into and out of the same stack that contains critical return addresses for the procedure calls.
[src:depth-first-search-algorithm/stack-abstract-data-type] If data is moved to the wrong location on the stack, or an oversized data item is moved to a stack location that is not large enough to contain it, return information for procedure calls may be corrupted, causing the program to fail.
[src:depth-first-search-algorithm/stack-abstract-data-type] Malicious parties may attempt a stack smashing attack that takes advantage of this type of implementation by providing oversized data input to a program that does not check the length of input.
[src:depth-first-search-algorithm/stack-abstract-data-type] Such a program may copy the data in its entirety to a location on the stack, and in doing so, it may change the return addresses for procedures that have called it.
[src:depth-first-search-algorithm/stack-abstract-data-type] This type of attack is a variation on the buffer overflow attack and is an extremely frequent source of security breaches in software, mainly because some of the most popular compilers use a shared stack for both data and procedure calls, and do not verify the length of data items.
[src:depth-first-search-algorithm/stack-abstract-data-type] Frequently, programmers do not write code to verify the size of data items, either, and when an oversized or undersized data item is copied to the stack, a security breach may occur.
[src:depth-first-search-algorithm/tree-traversal] In computer science, **tree traversal** (also known as **tree search** and **walking the tree**) is a form of graph traversal and refers to the process of visiting (e.g. retrieving, updating, or deleting) each node in a tree data structure exactly once.
[src:depth-first-search-algorithm/tree-traversal] Such traversals are classified by the order in which the nodes are visited.
[src:depth-first-search-algorithm/tree-traversal] The following algorithms are described for a binary tree, but they may be generalized to other trees as well.
[src:depth-first-search-algorithm/tree-traversal] Unlike linked lists, one-dimensional arrays and other linear data structures, which are canonically traversed in linear order, trees may be traversed in multiple ways.
[src:depth-first-search-algorithm/tree-traversal] They may be traversed in depth-first or breadth-first order.
[src:depth-first-search-algorithm/tree-traversal] There are three common ways to traverse them in depth-first order: in-order, pre-order and post-order.
[src:depth-first-search-algorithm/tree-traversal] Beyond these basic traversals, various more complex or hybrid schemes are possible, such as depth-limited searches like iterative deepening depth-first search.
[src:depth-first-search-algorithm/tree-traversal] The latter, as well as breadth-first search, can also be used to traverse infinite trees, see below.
[src:depth-first-search-algorithm/tree-traversal] Traversing a tree involves iterating over all nodes in some manner.
[src:depth-first-search-algorithm/tree-traversal] Because from a given node there is more than one possible next node (it is not a linear data structure), then, assuming sequential computation (not parallel), some nodes must be deferred—stored in some way for later visiting.
[src:depth-first-search-algorithm/tree-traversal] This is often done via a stack (LIFO) or queue (FIFO).
[src:depth-first-search-algorithm/tree-traversal] As a tree is a self-referential (recursively defined) data structure, traversal can be defined by recursion or, more subtly, corecursion, in a natural and clear fashion; in these cases the deferred nodes are stored implicitly in the call stack.
[src:depth-first-search-algorithm/tree-traversal] Depth-first search is easily implemented via a stack, including recursively (via the call stack), while breadth-first search is easily implemented via a queue, including corecursively.
[src:depth-first-search-algorithm/tree-traversal] In *depth-first search* (DFS), the search tree is deepened as much as possible before going to the next sibling.
[src:depth-first-search-algorithm/tree-traversal] Execute the following three operations in a certain order: N: Visit the current node.
[src:depth-first-search-algorithm/tree-traversal] L: Recursively traverse the current node's left subtree.
[src:depth-first-search-algorithm/tree-traversal] R: Recursively traverse the current node's right subtree.
[src:depth-first-search-algorithm/tree-traversal] The trace of a traversal is called a sequentialisation of the tree.
[src:depth-first-search-algorithm/tree-traversal] The traversal trace is a list of each visited node.
[src:depth-first-search-algorithm/tree-traversal] No one sequentialisation according to pre-, in- or post-order describes the underlying tree uniquely.
[src:depth-first-search-algorithm/tree-traversal] Given a tree with distinct elements, either pre-order or post-order paired with in-order is sufficient to describe the tree uniquely.
[src:depth-first-search-algorithm/tree-traversal] However, pre-order with post-order leaves some ambiguity in the tree structure.
[src:depth-first-search-algorithm/tree-traversal] There are three methods at which position of the traversal relative to the node (in the figure: red, green, or blue) the visit of the node shall take place.
[src:depth-first-search-algorithm/tree-traversal] The choice of exactly one color determines exactly one visit of a node as described below.
[src:depth-first-search-algorithm/tree-traversal] Recursively traverse the current node's left subtree.
[src:depth-first-search-algorithm/tree-traversal] Recursively traverse the current node's right subtree.
[src:depth-first-search-algorithm/tree-traversal] The pre-order traversal is a topologically sorted one, because a parent node is processed before any of its child nodes is done.
[src:depth-first-search-algorithm/tree-traversal] Visit the current node (in the figure: position blue).
[src:depth-first-search-algorithm/tree-traversal] Post-order traversal can be useful to get postfix expression of a binary expression tree.
[src:depth-first-search-algorithm/tree-traversal] Visit the current node (in the figure: position green).
[src:depth-first-search-algorithm/tree-traversal] In a binary search tree ordered such that in each node the key is greater than all keys in its left subtree and less than all keys in its right subtree, in-order traversal retrieves the keys in *ascending* sorted order.
[src:depth-first-search-algorithm/tree-traversal] In a binary search tree ordered such that in each node the key is greater than all keys in its left subtree and less than all keys in its right subtree, reverse in-order traversal retrieves the keys in *descending* sorted order.
[src:depth-first-search-algorithm/tree-traversal] Visit the current node for pre-order traversal.
[src:depth-first-search-algorithm/tree-traversal] Visit the current node for in-order traversal.
[src:depth-first-search-algorithm/tree-traversal] Recursively traverse the current node's last subtree.
[src:depth-first-search-algorithm/tree-traversal] Visit the current node for post-order traversal.
[src:depth-first-search-algorithm/tree-traversal] Depending on the problem at hand, pre-order, post-order, and especially one of the number of subtrees − 1 in-order operations may be optional.
[src:depth-first-search-algorithm/tree-traversal] Also, in practice more than one of pre-order, post-order, and in-order operations may be required.
[src:depth-first-search-algorithm/tree-traversal] For example, when inserting into a ternary tree, a pre-order operation is performed by comparing items.
[src:depth-first-search-algorithm/tree-traversal] A post-order operation may be needed afterwards to re-balance the tree.
[src:depth-first-search-algorithm/tree-traversal] In *breadth-first search* (BFS) or *level-order search*, the search tree is broadened as much as possible before going to the next depth.
[src:depth-first-search-algorithm/tree-traversal] There are also tree traversal algorithms that classify as neither depth-first search nor breadth-first search.
[src:depth-first-search-algorithm/tree-traversal] One such algorithm is Monte Carlo tree search, which concentrates on analyzing the most promising moves, basing the expansion of the search tree on random sampling of the search space.
[src:depth-first-search-algorithm/tree-traversal] Pre-order traversal can be used to make a prefix expression (Polish notation) from expression trees: traverse the expression tree pre-orderly.
[src:depth-first-search-algorithm/tree-traversal] For example, traversing the depicted arithmetic expression in pre-order yields "+ * *A* − *B* *C* + *D* *E*".
[src:depth-first-search-algorithm/tree-traversal] In prefix notation, there is no need for any parentheses as long as each operator has a fixed number of operands.
[src:depth-first-search-algorithm/tree-traversal] Pre-order traversal is also used to create a copy of the tree.
[src:depth-first-search-algorithm/tree-traversal] Post-order traversal can generate a postfix representation (Reverse Polish notation) of a binary tree.
[src:depth-first-search-algorithm/tree-traversal] Traversing the depicted arithmetic expression in post-order yields "*A* *B* *C* − * *D* *E* + +"; the latter can easily be transformed into machine code to evaluate the expression by a stack machine.
[src:depth-first-search-algorithm/tree-traversal] Post-order traversal is also used to delete the tree.
[src:depth-first-search-algorithm/tree-traversal] Each node is freed after freeing its children.
[src:depth-first-search-algorithm/tree-traversal] In-order traversal is very commonly used on binary search trees because it returns values from the underlying set in order, according to the comparator that set up the binary search tree.
[src:depth-first-search-algorithm/tree-traversal] Below are examples of stack-based implementation for pre-order, post-order and in-order traversal in recursive approach (left) as well as iterative approach (right).
[src:depth-first-search-algorithm/tree-traversal] Implementations in iterative approach are able to avoid the drawbacks of recursion, particularly limitations of stack space and performance issues.
[src:depth-first-search-algorithm/tree-traversal] Several alternative implementations are also mentioned.
[src:depth-first-search-algorithm/tree-traversal] The `node` to be started with may have been found in the binary search tree `bst` by means of a standard **search** function, which is shown here in an implementation without parent pointers, i.e. it uses a `stack` for holding the ancestor pointers.
[src:depth-first-search-algorithm/tree-traversal] Note that the function does not use keys, which means that the sequential structure is completely recorded by the binary search tree’s edges.
[src:depth-first-search-algorithm/tree-traversal] For traversals without change of direction, the (amortised) average complexity is ${\mathcal {O}}(1),$ because a full traversal takes $2n-2$ steps for a BST of size $n,$ 1 step for edge up and 1 for edge down.
[src:depth-first-search-algorithm/tree-traversal] The worst-case complexity is ${\mathcal {O}}(h)$ with h as the height of the tree.
[src:depth-first-search-algorithm/tree-traversal] All the above implementations require stack space proportional to the height of the tree which is a call stack for the recursive and a parent (ancestor) stack for the iterative ones.
[src:depth-first-search-algorithm/tree-traversal] In a poorly balanced tree, this can be considerable.
[src:depth-first-search-algorithm/tree-traversal] With the iterative implementations we can remove the stack requirement by maintaining parent pointers in each node, or by threading the tree (next section).
[src:depth-first-search-algorithm/tree-traversal] A binary tree is threaded by making every left child pointer (that would otherwise be null) point to the in-order predecessor of the node (if it exists) and every right child pointer (that would otherwise be null) point to the in-order successor of the node (if it exists).
[src:depth-first-search-algorithm/tree-traversal] We can make only one traversal at a time.
[src:depth-first-search-algorithm/tree-traversal] It is more prone to errors when both the children are not present and both values of nodes point to their ancestors.
[src:depth-first-search-algorithm/tree-traversal] Revert the changes to restore original tree.
[src:depth-first-search-algorithm/tree-traversal] Also, listed below is pseudocode for a simple queue based level-order traversal, and will require space proportional to the maximum number of nodes at a given depth.
[src:depth-first-search-algorithm/tree-traversal] This can be as much as half the total number of nodes.
[src:depth-first-search-algorithm/tree-traversal] A more space-efficient approach for this type of traversal can be implemented using an iterative deepening depth-first search.
[src:depth-first-search-algorithm/tree-traversal] While traversal is usually done for trees with a finite number of nodes (and hence finite depth and finite branching factor) it can also be done for infinite trees.
[src:depth-first-search-algorithm/tree-traversal] This is of particular interest in functional programming (particularly with lazy evaluation), as infinite data structures can often be easily defined and worked with, though they are not (strictly) evaluated, as this would take infinite time.
[src:depth-first-search-algorithm/tree-traversal] Some finite trees are too large to represent explicitly, such as the game tree for chess or Go, and so it is useful to analyze them as if they were infinite.
[src:depth-first-search-algorithm/tree-traversal] A basic requirement for traversal is to visit every node eventually.
[src:depth-first-search-algorithm/tree-traversal] For infinite trees, simple algorithms often fail this.
[src:depth-first-search-algorithm/tree-traversal] For example, given a binary tree of infinite depth, a depth-first search will go down one side (by convention the left side) of the tree, never visiting the rest, and indeed an in-order or post-order traversal will never visit *any* nodes, as it has not reached a leaf (and in fact never will).
[src:depth-first-search-algorithm/tree-traversal] By contrast, a breadth-first (level-order) traversal will traverse a binary tree of infinite depth without problem, and indeed will traverse any tree with bounded branching factor.
[src:depth-first-search-algorithm/tree-traversal] By contrast, a breadth-first search will never reach the grandchildren, as it seeks to exhaust the children first.
[src:depth-first-search-algorithm/tree-traversal] A more sophisticated analysis of running time can be given via infinite ordinal numbers; for example, the breadth-first search of the depth 2 tree above will take ω·2 steps: ω for the first level, and then another ω for the second level.
[src:depth-first-search-algorithm/tree-traversal] Thus, simple depth-first or breadth-first searches do not traverse every infinite tree, and are not efficient on very large trees.
[src:depth-first-search-algorithm/tree-traversal] However, hybrid methods can traverse any (countably) infinite tree, essentially via a diagonal argument ("diagonal"—a combination of vertical and horizontal—corresponds to a combination of depth and breadth).
[src:depth-first-search-algorithm/tree-traversal] Concretely, given the infinitely branching tree of infinite depth, label the root (), the children of the root (1), (2), ..., the grandchildren (1, 1), (1, 2), ..., (2, 1), (2, 2), ..., and so on.
